<Time>1594328237400< /Time>< GmapID>
0x80e830bccd7de641:0xafcda73403f35038</GmapID>
<username>Cyn Thompson< /username>< Review>
The really enjoy eating at Panda Express. They're a little more on the expensive side in terms of fast food restaurants so it's kind of a special treat when I do go there for my family. My problem is with the soy sauce. I happen to really enjoy my Chinese food a lot more when I have soy sauce with it. For some reason at Panda Express they make you ask for the soy sauce when you at the register when you pay for your order. That is fine. But when the cashier acts as though they are going way out of their way to get you some or simply lies to you completely about putting some in your bag already, that's what irks me. That's exactly what happened to me three nights ago. I didn't realize until I got home, a few miles away from the store that the cashier lied to my face and put no soy sauce packets in my bag. They act like the cost for those packets come out of their daily wages or something. I realize I can go to the grocery store and buy some for myself which is what I'll do, but my point is that's something they provide with your meal there and why should I be made to feel like I'm bothering the staff for asking for some or just flat out be lied to? I know I'm not the only person who feels this way about Panda Express, I've spoken to many people who all feel the same way. I wonder how many  customers they've lost over this.</Review>

< review>
The food here is great. The service however is almost comically unacceptable. The woman that owns the place is a bit nasty to customers and I don't think she cares. She likely does not know how nasty she is to be honest, but that doesn't make it okay. Several mistakes were made to my group's order. When we asked the management to make good on this they were a bit annoyed that we asked them to redo our food and give us what we had paid for. These mistakes happen almost every time I have been there. The food is good, so I keep giving it a chance for some reason. The managers also seem to have similar nasty attitudes. Not what you would call a welcoming place. The setting and food is decent, however. I can't say it doesn't have good food. If you are looking for a lunch spot that is welcoming, friendly, and provides good service, this is not the place for you.</review>

< Review>
The prices listed online are extremely misleading. A boarding fee per night is to be expected but the additional daily fee to have someone watch your dog, plus mandatory insurance, plus an additional fee if you can‚Äôt pick up by 1pm, and another fee on top of that if you can‚Äôt pick up by 7 has you spending more than twice what you should. God forbid you forget to bring treats from home.

Money aside, when I picked up my dog, they told me she‚Äôd had a bit of diarrhea, which they said was probably just stress. She came back extremely sick. She‚Äôd lost a lot of weight, was sneezing, choking, vomiting, and had uncontrollable diarrhea. On top of that, she howls when left alone, which is the primary reason I didn‚Äôt leave her alone at home while I was gone. When I picked her up from this place, she had completely lost her voice. It‚Äôs been two weeks and her voice is still very hoarse. Therefore I have every reason to believe she was left alone for the entirety of her stay, excluding her occasional potty breaks and very expensive scratches on the head.

Pros:
Polite staff.
They gave me an update on her eating habits.
They opened their doors late so I could still pick her up after my flight had been delayed. (But then they charged me $25 for it)< /Review>

< Review>
Christie is an amazing trainer! We have worked with 3 trainers before finding her, and none of them were able to help our dog Harper. He was having issues socializing with other dogs, it was so bad that we couldn't really walk him because if we saw another dog he would lose him mind, oh it was horrible and so embarrassing. 105457652788231355294<//user_id>
< name>
Jane Adams< /name>
<date>1575555991612< /date><rate>4<//rate>< review>
BETTER THAN MOST

It's very challenging finding dog boarding or dog day care and trust strangers with your furry family member. Some places I've brought my dog too had great first impressions and then quickly becomes a horrifying experience after actually bringing your dog there. I was tipped off about Paw Commons and heard nothing but good stuff. This review is specifically for this locations.

But first... let me get this out the way
1. Hillcrest is the only location that has indoor and outdoor playrooms. Bay Park and Encinitas locations only offer indoor playrooms.
2. The trade-off, Bay Park and Encinitas offers Standard rooms AND Luxury Suites for dog boarding. Hillcrest only offers Standard rooms.
3. No overnight staff at any of the locations. And limited hours of drop-off and pick-up.
4. They have cameras in the playrooms
5. They separate small dog from big dogs

THE EXPERIENCE.
They require Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella, and a temperament assessment. By this time, Chloe is use to having temperament assessments every weekend (we've checked out many pet resorts). I decided to bring Chloe to the Bay Park location since I reserved a Luxury Suite when I go on travel (although I prefer to her be at the Hillcrest location). Temperament Assessment is not free like other places - the cost is $10 and they keep her for 4hrs minimum. I dropped her off and the staff seemed like they haven't yet woken up from the weekend. It was I who has to initiate what needs to happen by asking alot of questions. After 4+ hrs I picked her up and again no comments. I had to ask a bunch of questions for them to basically say she did well. Please staff, be more vocal. I asked for a tour and they called someone from the reservation team who was super vocal and friendly - I liked her vibe more than the front staff, she was more welcoming and didn't sound dead. I am so happy I reserved the Luxury Suite for my dog, its a big room with a high bed, couch, and flat screen tv - makes them feel like home. I did see the Standard room and was impressed that it's very spacious - imagine a tall room with the width of a twin size bed. Overall, Chloe seemed happy coming out of this place. I even spied on her on the camera and was happy to see the playrooms were not packed and all dogs were getting along and she was being taken care of.

So far, so good.

Until the next review...</review>

<Text>Pros- Indoors and air conditioned, big dogs and small dogs are separated, web camera, great price, the trainer spent a lot of time with me explaining her program, everyone seems nice enough.

The dogs are just walking around aimlessly. My puppy came home tired, but not due to play, she didn't nap all day, likely due to anxiety being in a new place.  Another downside is the dogs pee and poop right there INSIDE. I realize they cannot have an indoor play area and take dogs outside individually, but I personally don't want to erase my housebreaking efforts.

<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
I have had a great experience with The Golden Paw over the last few years and highly recommend their day play and boarding to anyone looking to put their dogs in a safe, clean environment while they are either at work or on vacation.

We have used many of their competitors in the past and this is the first time that I have actually taken the time to write a review because I was so happy with the service that I received.

The staff at the Golden Paw really take pride in what they do and it shows.  Jessica, Tiffany and Kelly are awesome and they are always happy to help with keeping our dogs happy and healthy during their stay.  I cannot tell you how much we appreciate their willingness to help with our last minute plans, whether it be heading out of town last minute or getting caught in a meeting and not being able to pick the dogs up on time.

With two kids and everything that comes along with that, it is very nice to have such a great staff at The Golden Paw keeping our dogs happy and safe until we can get there.  We have two pretty high maintenance dogs (a short hair pointer and a miniature pincher) and both are worn out from play at the end of the day when they get home so I know that they love the experience also.

In fact when I first started going there it was like pulling them into the front door of the vet's office with all four paws locked up and being dragged across the floor.  Now they are both pulling their way into the lobby once we get to the parking lot and they really seem to be having a good time when we check in on them from the web cams.

Our dogs are really a part of our family and that is why I wanted to take a moment to write this review and hopefully give other people the piece of mind in knowing that the Golden Paw really is a great place to send your furry little family members.</text>

<review>Fantastic vegan Vietnamese food at a place that is a bit run down, but you won‚Äôt be disappointed by the flavors and textures. I had the fried rice with 2 main dish choices for $9 and an even $10 with a Soda. Cash only.

Staff are friendly and its fun to listen to them speaking Vietnamese amongst themselves and with some local regulars.

The owner said he opened this shop more than 35 years ago after coming from Vietnam. The vegan ‚Äòmeats‚Äô were originally made using bananas, but they now use soy base or jackfruit.

The vegan kebabs and chicken were really tasty and filling. I‚Äôd been frustrated by the lack of vegetarian options when I visited Vietnam in the 90‚Äôs, but the owners assured me I would find a lot of great options now. Such friendly people.

For sustainability, eat-in diners on reusable plates and utensils but to-go in plastic packaging in plastic bags it seems (so bring your own to save in take-out waste if you can).</review></record>

< review>
what to order: Bun Bo Hue chay
tip: metered street parking, ca$h only

I love eating Vietnamese vegetarian food because we do it so darn well  and Tofoo Com Chay definitely did not disappoint!

I wish I could have taken some to-go but I didn't bring enough cash.

The Bun Bo Hue was a good size for lunch, flavorful and full of veggies. It wasn't the best Bun Bo Hue Chay I've had but it was good and hit the spot.

While I was eating, a lot of customers came in to order their various dishes. They have several combo options- similar to when you go to a Chinese styrofoam box type place.

Would definitely come back to support the mom&pop restaurant!<//review>

< name>
DanneX</name>
< Time>
1572554183864</Time>
< Rate>
2< /Rate>
< Review>
First off, it's great to know that this small whole in the wall is trying to do veggie/vegan vietnamese.

It came recommend from a friend and unfortunately it did not meet the hype and expectations.

I was disappointed to experience difficulty navigating and understanding their menu. While the food is "cheap" it lacked in flavor and freshness.

I visited around the lunch hour and it was evident that the food had been sitting around from the AM. I chose to try their Sesame Veggie Chicken Sandwich. I was pleasantly surprised when a fresh roll of bread was placed in the oven to crisp up. That's where the glam of the sandwich ended. Next the "meat" was pre-made and microwaved to serve. The "meat" lacked flavor and quickly became cold.

Additionally, I ordered their Summer Rolls. I was happy that a range of "meats" where inside the rolls. The sauce that accompanied the rolls was the one thing that saved both my rolls and sandwich.

I do not plan to return. I think the idea is great and as a vegetarian, I am always looking for new and creative ways to enjoy food. Tofoo; however, did not live up to its hype and at best, I didn't even "get what I paid for."<//Review>

I highly recommend the special fried rice, the teriyaki chicken kababs, the spicy noodle soup, and the vermechelli noodle soup! They DO make the food ahead of time and microwave it, just in case you have a problem with that. It's cash only!</Text>

< text>
This place was pretty good. We went on a Saturday around 11:00 am and there was a line to check out only. We didn't have to wait to get in. I got the sourdough bread, cinnamon raisin bread, and m&m cookies. The sourdough was my favorite and toasts really well on a griddle. I wasn't too fond of the cookies. They are hard. Not bad but I like softer cookies. They still had a good taste though, very buttery. I liked the atmosphere and was going to stop by there again on the way home from Mammoth bit the line was out the door and around the building.< /text>

<user_name>Ryan Barr<//user_name><text>Oh man, what's not to love about this place?! If you enjoy any type of baked good, this is your stop. One side of the bakery is focused on bread, and the other is cookies and pastries. It's pretty magical.<//text><Date>1620232003433< /Date><Rate>5<//Rate>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
</record></dataset><record>
< gmapID>
0x80be1600fb5ec2ff:0xcfcedd18fdb08a6e< /gmapID>
<Response>None< /Response>< rating>
4</rating>
< Review>
I stopped here on my way home from Lake Tahoe. I wanted to stop on my way up originally, but the line was unbelievably long and just not worth it. Thankfully it was more reasonable on my way back and I was able to stop. The line moved pretty quickly and they had a mist machine over the line (which was nice, but a little too strong as it actually got our clothes a little wet). There are quite a few tables out front for eating.

The inside was pretty crowded and people weren't really following social distancing. Everyone was required to wear masks though.

The pastry and food are separate lines while the rest of the baked goods are all spread out around the store. There are no prices listed on or by the items, instead there are laminated sheets with prices listed so you need to know what the item you are interested in is called in order to know the price. All the pastries were unlabeled so I had to point and ask what something was and then check the price. This is not a great system because it takes a lot longer and then the lines are slower.

Prices are as expected. A little on the pricy side, but I get that it's a popular place and kind of a tourist destination.

The food and everything tasted really good. I had a good overall experience.< /Review>

<user_name>Stacy Colledge<//user_name>< Review>
This place could not be more delicious and delightful. It's our pitstop every time we come home from Mammoth, which is about once a month. My favorites include the bacon/egg/cheese croissant, the DARK chocolate peanut butter cup, the poppy seed muffin and my mocha coffee with two pumps peppermint. Some other faves include the pull apart bread and the coffee cake. This place is an absolute MUST!!</Review>

<userid>104315430881787977254<//userid><date>1599492367644< /date><pictures>None</pictures>< username>
Pravin Prakash</username>
< review>
I think I got caught up in the hype train as well.
Though this review is obviously based only on the things I tried - chocolate croissant, some apple dessert pastry, and a cinnamon bread stick. And the amount of time it takes.

The place is honestly fine. But I really don't think it's worth the wait in the line. I went in at 7:15a thinking that was a good time. (Just figured I can't rhyme. Anymore üò¨).

Anyways, there was a 15 person line by the time I got there. The line outside moves pretty fast to be honest, but the line once you are inside (to pay) takes forever!

The bakery is huge and they have racks and racks of breads and various bakery items. It's very difficult to socially distance, once you're inside. But they do mandate masks, which is good.

I walked around lost not knowing what to get - ended up picking up some of the things I saw others picking up lol.

The croissant was alright. Especially if you're expecting something amazing, you will be disappointed. There is not a lot of effort made into the layering of the croissant, which makes it not particularly crispy at all.
The apple dessert pastey was meh. Same issue with the bread being all soggy.
The cinnamon bread stick was pretty bad. I could only eat a part of it before I threw it away.

I was expecting the items to be at least warm, given that I was picking up so early in the morning. They were not warm at all. Makes me wonder when the baking is done.

I have an apple pullaway and an apple strudel, that I haven't tried yet. Hopefully they are good.

Given the number of pastries they make on a daily basis, I guess it's understandable that they don't put in the effort to make all individual pastries taste and feel good. So it depends on what you are going here for - as long as you don't expect amazing stuff, you won't be as disappointed.

Also, try to find a time when there is not a lot of people waiting to get inside.</review>

<userid>112402214680656830849</userid><Response>None<//Response>< text>
This is our official family road trip stop! This is carb heaven! Delicious, all natural, breads, sweets, and, treats. We always get a sandwich (don't forget to order your cheese). For snack, I LOVE their cheese and garlic breads slices. (The cheese is thick and the garlic spicy-fresh). All the different bread loaves are delicious. The kids love the strudels, doughnuts, cookies, etc. Still haven't tried their gelato, yet... In short, the options are overwhelming, which is one reason why this place is so amazing. To not stop here would be one your biggest regrets in life. Before you pay for your kids to go to college, GO TO ERICK SCHAT'S BAKERY!!! Thrice.</text>

Wonderland! This is my favorite stop while driving on highway CA 395. It's a treat to the eyes to walk around inside the bakery. So many quality products, you name it. < Text>
Great bakery with good bread, pastries, and sandwiches. They also stock a wide variety of jams and oils. The shop can be a bit crowded between the narrow isles and all the people, so if you have a backpack on be sure to watch where you're walking. I tried the Mule Kick and Hot Pastrami sandwiches and thought they were both really good - tasty, and a generous portion for the price. There's also a vegetarian option for people who want that.</Text>

< Review>
This place is awesome! Fun stop! Provides a hint at old ways and feels of bread making. Tidbits of historical info/stuff throughout. Some items are not the best you'll ever taste but, are also not full of lab experiments for flavor, color, and preservation either. There are so many items that are a delight that meet the mood of our palate each time we stop. The place has changed a little over time but, still offers a great variety of baked/bakery items and sweets. Each time we stop it's great because they provide us with good options for meals for camping, backpacking, and easily assembled road trip meals on-the-go. Thank you Schat's!</Review>

<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN_w-NZwfoNpYVHuRWJWXlq3pr6SNbVeBNZZZhh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNnFB1yLYKgg7kD-6gI-PzQyiMpqnS3UA0Z_z_6=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics>< Review>
You're probably not going here just for the bakery. You're on your way somewhere else. Then you see Erick Schat's Bakery, or you've heard of it, anyway - there's a line of cars. The parking lot is crowded. The licence plates show visitors from multiple states. You decide to go in.

Heavenly smells of baked goods, fresh breads, cocoa and coffee, and a sight to behold - more flavours and types of bread than you've ever seen. All fresh, all delicious, all immediately making you crave the carby goodness.

No matter if you're here for sandwich bread, moist cakes, cheesy breadsticks or an arrangement of baked goods - you'll leave the store happy with hands full of their products. And you'll love every single thing.<//Review>

<Rate>5</Rate><Text>Always the place to stop, both coming to Mammoth Mountain and going home from Mammoth Mountain. The bakery is filled with breads, cookies, pastries, donuts, and candy. The deli features sandwiches, bread by the loaf, sauces and jams. There is always a line in both sections of the bakery. Outside features some photo opportunity places featuring a wood bear as selfie site and an old time delivery van. The staff is a bit abrupt, but who wouldn't be with tourists coming in all day, probably asking the same questions. The Erick's Schat's Bakery in Mammoth is nice too, but just does not have as much as the one in Bishop. Stop at this one for your eating enjoyment supplies.</Text></record></dataset><record>

<Text>You cannot leave Bishop without eating at Schat's Bakery.
This is a bakery like no other, a tourist attraction and lunch place and sensory delight. They do not allow photos inside so getting one is hard.
There is plenty of free parking off street, and the bakery is easy to find on Main Street. I enjoyed the gelato very much.
Honey and jams and jellies are sold, but not made onsite. I was surprised to see Jams from Maine. I tried to buy local honey and ended up with some made by bees in Independence, 45 miles away.
If you are not hungry when you pull up, don't worry. Go inside anyway and stroll through the narrow walkways between racks piled high with good things, look at the array of bakery treats and smell the air. After a short time, you'll wanting to taste more than just the plentiful samples. Get in line...eat inside or out on the sidewalk.<//Text>< gmap_id>
0x80be1600fb5ec2ff:0xcfcedd18fdb08a6e</gmap_id>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
Great Bakery ! My family have been coming to Schat's Bishop for over 50 years. We have made this place a tradition while driving back from Mammoth and Lake Tahoe to LA. The turkey sandwiches are carved right in front you and delicious ! All the freshly made breads are fantastic. My favorite are the Raisin breads and cheese breads right from the oven early in the morning. Also, the pastries and cookies are great !< /Text>

A must stop to shop place for anyone who loves bread and sweet baked goods.
Its6 a bakery and cafe. VERY busy on Fridays, Saturdays, Sundays and holidays. Even weekdays can be busy.
The rule in our family is, if you go by there, you must stop and shop for everyone!! It's  all yummy.
We do stop with grandkids and it takes forever for them to make up their minds, too much good stuff.
Parking around back, but can be very tight for large pickup trucks and small motorhomes.</Review>

< text>
Great bakery with 2 locations. The one in Mammoth is the standard bakery with sandwich shop the one in Bishop is larger with an added gelato stand. Both have a pet friendly patio. Expect lots of people on holiday weekends. Great breads and the sandwiches are large enough to share. The Chili-Cheese bread is a must try!<//text>

<Rating>4</Rating>< review>
Always packed, but the quality of the baked goods is beyond just a tourist trap, and it is definitely worth the visit for the pull apart buns alone.

The only thing that marred the experience was the barista refusing to make a coffee in a reusable mug for the customer ahead of us in line, basically saying, "We'll make it in a disposable cup then you can pour it in your own mug," which totally defeats the purpose of trying to save resources. It seemed the employee was just following policy, so management really needs to rethink their responsibility to the planet, when there are other coffee shops out there who give *discounts* for bringing your own mug.<//review>

<Text>Oh my goodness it's bread heaven! <userid>111718164741871343458<//userid><Name>Bea Kissinger<//Name><Time>1601238334675< /Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
Bread galore. Different types of bread for all your special needs. Pastries so beautifully displayed and so easy going in my mouth... YUMMY.

This detour heading home from Lake Tahoe was definitely worth my derailed diet.

- Whole Pastrami Sandwich on rye bread (not toasted - I think you can request to toast the bread, but from what I have seen they don't do it, unless asked) SO DAMN GOOD I ATE THE WHOLE THING. Hello love handles!

- Veggie Sandwich - instead of Gouda Cheese we got cheddar cheese. That was just as delicious.

- Pastries: Fruit Tart and rasberry type bread (whatever you get I am sure you will be happy). I also bought some danishes for my office. They seemed to love them as well.

Warning: This place gets crowded. So be patient, it's worth it.<//Text>

< text>
Come here! We recently took a road trip to Tahoe from San Diego. 9 hours on the road starting on a light breakfast. We entered Bishop with an appetite like no other and stopped at Erick Schat's Bakery to grab a sandwich. I ordered the Sheepherders Bread Ham sandwich. Amazing! Filling and light at the same time. The ham was juicy and pleasantly not tasting of preservatives. The word on the street was they use fresh cuts of meat. Let me tell you, you can taste the difference and its a difference you will continue to want after you finish your sandwich. The green leaf lettuce was crunchy, the tomato juicy, the deli mustard üëç on point! The Sheepherders bread slices were exactly like I wanted. Typically I order sourdough so I enjoy thicker, full bread. The Sheepherders bread was everyrhing I wanted.
Come to Erick Schat's Bakery and order a sandwich. You will enjoy every bite. Then head across the street to enjoy it in the cool shade on the grass among the trees. After you're done, do yourself a favor and order another to go, because in an hour you will be wishing you had another!< /text>

< review>
This place is overwhelming in an amazing way! There are sooo many delicious options. My boyfriend used to stop at this bakery with his family on the way to and from Mammoth. Safe to say we will be making that a tradition as well.

This trip we bought 2 original cheeze breads, a garlic cheeze bread, macaroons, and the apricot coffee cake. The coffee cake is addicting!

Tip: If you are not a huge bread person (or you want your bread to last), Cut your bread into 2-4 pieces and freeze it. Then you can defrost as you please over the course of 3 months or so.

Eating a macaroon as I write this....<//review>

<time>1554605764729</time><userid>113878263300592622944<//userid><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Review>
This is a large bakery and sweet shop, with loaves of bread (savory and sweet), donuts, gelato, and pastries. There's room to eat inside or outside. The parking is free and plentiful. The employees were polite and professional. The place was clearly patronized by locals (not just tourists). I got a pecan roll and a raspberry cream cheese croissant. Both were good, very tasty and not overly sweet. But neither were amazing. The pecan roll was a little too crusty. I also had a jack cheese roll. It was a bit dry and could have used more flavor.<//Review>

< Name>

116148105652673134734<//user_id>
<response>None<//response>< Time>
1538236116301</Time>
< GmapID>
0x80be1600fb5ec2ff:0xcfcedd18fdb08a6e< /GmapID>
<Rate>4< /Rate>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
< review>
If you are heading to Bishop California, then add Schat's Bakery to you "Must Do ", list. I suggest saving room for lunch as their sandwiches are made with roasted turkey carved right off of the bird and amazingly fresh baked bread. They have all types of meats, but the turkey is truly outstanding. Then for desert grab a loaf (or two because you will want more, trust me), of Cinnamon pull-apart bread and  some of there butter cookies and enjoy carb heaven. For an added treat pick up a bag of day old bread and walk across the street to the Visitors Center. The park is peaceful as well as beautiful, with plenty of picnic tables under shade trees and a little creek with hungry ducks.  A great way to decompress from the road and recharge your batteries. Oh,  on a side note if you like a little spice in your life the pepper cheese bread is yummy as well!</review>
</record>
</dataset><record>

<userid>106344764360116655200<//userid><Name>David Calhoun</Name>< Time>
1573048247610</Time>
<rate>3</rate>< text>
It's a fun place, but can be crazy during the day.  Somewhat of a tourist trap, but still worth the visit.  Highly recommend waking up early to avoid the crowds.

This has always been a 395 road trip stop for me since I was a kid.  Schat's is a fun stop for anything bread or sweets related, but there are better options in town for sandwiches (highly recommend Mahogany Meats) and for coffee (highly recommend Looney Bean coffee).

They used to have an awesome onion cheese bread, but they dropped it from the menu to make way for the bacon cheese bread, which is just meh.  Also, there used to be about 2x or 3x the amount of cheese in those breads long ago, in the 2000s.  Nowadays there is a really disappointing amount (this isn't a one-time judgement, it's something I have noticed in my last five or so visits recently).

For folks who want to taste what the onion cheese was like, or want a more generous helping of cheese, I highly recommend the onion focaccia bread.< /text>

<user>103883558813807132037<//user><name>Bobby Stephenson<//name><time>1526523908224< /time>< rate>
5</rate>
<Review>A must stop whenever I'm coming thru Bishop, and I try to come up with any excuse to drive the 5 hours over this beautiful area of California!  Where to start?!

Their breads beautifully aromatic and you will not go wrong with any kind that you choose, weather their classic chili cheese bread to their Rosemary Sourdough bread.

If you are coming for lunch or thinking about having delicious to eat for lunch please try their sandwiches! You honestly can't go wrong with any of what they have to offer, including their Thanksgiving dinner sandwich which you can have anytime of the year. For me? hot pastrami all day!

Looking for something to satisfy the sweet tooth? Have a look at the dozens of pastries they have to offer and pick what looks good to you.  Be careful though, you might find yourself picking up more than you bargained for. Is that a bad thing though? Also come to this section during the morning for some delicious breakfast sandwiches!

At the end of the pastry corner are drinks! Need a pick-me-up while you enjoy the drive along the majestic slopes of the Eastern Sierra? Have a coffee! They have so many choices and the drinks definitely compliment well with the pastries you just picked up.  Also, fresh orange juice throughout the day cam definitely help revitalize the body if you are making that road trip on 395.

All times of the year this place is packed! So be ready to spend some quality time here! Now to plan the next time I come back to Owens Valley...< /Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOJmF6VbSNJOlxmEmqNa-w1OPc1WE_1fQBNepIf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><Resp>None</Resp>< gmapID>

<review>Delicious bread, pastries, and sandwiches.  Note that each section closes at a different time.  The sandwich deli closes the earliest, followed by the bakery, and then the pastry area.  Definitely worth stopping by if you're headed up (or down) the 395.

<Name>Raymond Bailey</Name><Date>1507196173338< /Date>< Rating>
1<//Rating>
<text>BUYER BEWARE! This is NOT the Schat's Bakery it used to be!  Sold to another person the bread quality has decreased from its former 5 star level! The "Extra Sourdough" bread is AS flavorless and soft as white bread. The "Cinnamon Raisin" bread has holes the size of golf balls (literally). Though still a good tourist stop, it no longer has the high quality baking behind the original Schat's Bakery.  Too bad.
But as a welcome stop in the middle of the western desert? Not bad.<//text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Resp>None< /Resp><gmapID>0x80be1600fb5ec2ff:0xcfcedd18fdb08a6e<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<user>108726233374855271212< /user><name>James Costanzo<//name><Date>1471974876283< /Date>< rate>
4< /rate>
< Review>
A classic pit-stop for visitors to Bishop, or those passing through coming from LA and going to Mammoth, Tahoe, or any of the other great outdoor areas along the way.

I personally have been coming here since I was a kid, every time my family passed through Bishop while heading to Tahoe on the 395. Over the years my tastes have evolved, from sugary sweets to more simple breads, and Schat's has always had something to offer.

The breads, pastries, and all their bread products are top-notch. Are they the best in the world? Honest answer: No. Schat's does make an excellent bread, but over the years I have come to realize Schat's is great, but not amazing.

Schat's knows it has a huge appeal and tourist draw, and you can see it reflected in the prices. This is my one major gripes about the place, as the price of their breads and products can be on the high side. My advice is that if you have never had "Schat's" before, go for it and get yourself some bread, and form your own opinion.

I now personally don't stop here everytime I pass through Bishop, as I sometimes opt to just bring bread from a local bakery in my hometown. Whenever I do stop here though, it's always nice to revel in the memory and timelessness of a place that has been here for as long as I've known, and enjoy a nice loaf of bread for the journeys ahead.< /Review>

< review>
World-wide classic.  I have driven on 395 through Bishop on no less than 30 round trips.  Schat's is my "go to" place to eat and be recharged.  The food is simply amazing.  Fresh.  Delicious.  Filling.  The staff is friendly, despite the large number of customers.  The number of differnt languages spoken by the foreign travelers who stop to eat there is fun to count.  There is a new Deli in town.  I almost went there just to try something new, until I read all of the excellent reviews of the new Deli, which seemed to be written by friends of the new Deli and aimed at stating false information about the competitor Schat's.  I dream of eating at Schat's on my trips from Reno to Southern California - even though I have traveled to and eaten in 49 USA states and 40 countries!< /review>

< text>
First time going to the bakery. I'm only giving this place 3 stars because of the food. The service deserves a negative rating if possible. Lovely selection of breads, doughnuts, pastries, and many other things. Picked up Oregon Trail Strawberry Jam for my sister in Colorado, it's her favorite! However, it being my first visit I wasn't sure of the way things flowed, such as the line and what register was used for breads and pastries. There was no one around to ask. Wasn't even greeted when we walked in. When I got to the register the cashier was very rude. Her tone of voice and dirty looks because we didn't go through the line correctly was totally uncalled for. She kept starring with confusion the whole time I was checking out and making inappropriate faces. The employees need to be trained in greeting customers and not being rude. Will tell family and friends and not to go to the bakery any longer.<//text>

<userid>108611250887448167119<//userid><Name>Charley Carlin< /Name><Time>1506095459506</Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
Well it has been a while since I drove through Bishop. It seems that every trip requires a stop at Schat's. The choices are always so inviting that I find myself overbuying. It is magic to see and smell all the creations at this bakery. Schart's is a institution in Bishop, and is one of the crown jewels of the area.
This is always a must stop for every traveller in the area.
Baked goods, bread, cookies, jerky, sandwiches and more. It is even fun to watch the people be  entertained by the choices in the bakery.
This place is fun for everyone.</review>

<user_name>Tracy Franks-Blanchard< /user_name><Date>1407342876946< /Date>< Review>
The breads are very tasty and fresh.  The other bakery items are "okay" at best.  The service is what drives down my review.  We arrived at the sandwich counter only to be told they were out of all but two breads.  Fine, we opted for one of the choices available, but were then told they were out of cheese as well.  When I went to the other side to order some of their sweeter options, I couldn't get any service.  I finally settled for what I could serve myself on the pre-packaged shelves and checked out.  At the checkout, when asked if this was all I wanted, I explained how I hadn't gotten any service for the behind the counter items.  The cashier (Jose) laughed.  He didn't offer to help me, he didn't apologize for the shoddy service, just laughed.  When I asked him why he was laughing, he laughed more.  This place does not value the individual customer.  Great bread - SCH!Tservice.< /Review>

< user>
114264427988435665244<//user>
< Date>
1500270750876</Date>
< Rate>
1<//Rate>
< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< Text>
Schat's had been dear to my heart for the nearly 20 years of memories since first setting foot in the bakery, but a recent experience -- and the way our complaint was handled at both the shop and via email with a manager bearing the same last name as the shop's -- INSULTED us so much for something minor that could have easily been addressed, we will NEVER return. I decided to write this review after the manager failed to make things right and became silent despite multiple follow-ups.

Visiting Schat's had been both a family and road trip tradition for anyone coming with me to Yosemite/Mammoth/Mt Whitney. On July 3, 2017 around 2p, my wife, mother-in-law (MIL), and toddler son stopped by again on our way home from Lake Tahoe. We wanted to pick up some bread and honey for my MIL and another bread for my brother.

While waiting in line, I noticed a sign that stated that a Senior Discount was available. So, I asked, and the cashier said that the senior has to pay for the items. My MIL (a senior) told her that's fine, and was about to grab her wallet when she realized that she had left it in her car. I asked the cashier if we could put our purchase on hold so I could go grab her wallet (she was carrying my son), but then my wife noticed that I had cash and suggested to give it to MIL. The cashier told us in a very abrupt, RUDE TONE-OF-VOICE that the SENIOR has to pay for everything. Seeing me hand the cash to MIL would not qualify. MIL and I both told the cashier that this made no sense, but I went ahead and asked again if we could put our purchase on hold. Again, she rudely told us in a DEMEANING, annoyed manner the total price. At this point, I was about to walk out, but MIL was looking forward to the honey and bread, and I also did not want to disappoint my brother for not getting him his bread. So, I went ahead and paid, and without getting a "thank you for your purchase", we silently left the store and exchanged with one another how upset we were. A short while after, two customers who were in line behind us came by our car to tell us that the way we were treated was inappropriate.

We tried to brush off the experience and continued our journey home. About 15-30 minutes later, I found that all of us were still so upset, I decided to turn around to 1) return the items and 2) speak with a manager. We wanted to let management know that the Senior Discount sign never said that the Senior had to be the actual person paying, that we disagreed with the policy's strictness of not accepting cash given to the senior, and that we were insulted and mistreated. We also understood that there may be people abusing Senior Discounts, but no way should customers be treated the way we were -- POLITELY inform the customer of the policy and provide the option to put the purchase on hold to get the wallet. On a side note, what would stop me from just giving the cash to MIL outside? Was it really worth for the shop to insult customers with such a strict policy?

When I spoke with the pastry supervisor, she listened to what we had to say, and she saw how visibly upset we were. She listened and we appreciated her for that. We were then referred to the bakery supervisor, and as we walked there, we found something SHOCKING: the supervisor was with the cashier the entire time when the incident happened! She was THERE and had done NOTHING about it! We told her our story and explained that we did NOT return for the Senior discount (a mere $3.xx - return gas costs more), but as a matter of principle to discuss the policy and experience. Yet, she decided to just refund that amount and without even an apology (or a small "we are sorry" pastry -- didn't have to be much!) We were going nowhere, and I decided to write management instead once we got home.

Management responded with an apology, noted that she heard of the incident, and would follow up. That never happened despite multiple emails to her the past 2 weeks. Businesses sometimes forget that customers are the reason for their existence. Sadly, Schat's apparently is TOO SUCCESSFUL to care.</Text>

< Text>
This place has a large variety of quality baked goods. The prices are generally high compared to similar bakeries elsewhere. Most of the prices are either poorly marked, unmarked, or given by weight (probably to hide the actual cost). As with another reviewer, we made the mistake of buying a peanut butter cup before discovering that it was more than $5. Although only the server had touched it (when placing it in a bag), we were told we could not return it.
An OK place to visit if you don't care about price or service.< /Text>

< Text>
Very fun eclectic vintage place with lots of bakery products and a line up for freshly made sandwiches. No 3 Pastrami was awesome! It's a perfect stop in Bishop before or after hitting the Mammoth slopes. They got a huge variety of breads, focaccia, bread sticks (bacon cheese too), sweets, cakes, donuts, cookies, ice cream and espresso. No gluten-free or vegan bakery items though. It's a traditional long time establishment, that's a must tourist/break stop.<//Text>

<time>1505167405001<//time><rate>2<//rate><text>Stopped by here twice, once on the way to Tahoe and on the way back because many people know of it. I have to say, I have never felt so let down by an eatery with such a high review score. It was overpriced to start, we got a bagel egg and cheese sandwich that was only ok, the cinnamon roll and strawberry turnover were both pretty good. Total price was a joke, the wait was pretty long as well. Overall it is not really any better than starbucks, the jams and whatnot, while numerous, we're very expensive. I was going to try to get a sandwich on the trip back but the line was comically long and honestly they didn't look to be worth anywhere near the 10 bucks you pay. Gf wanted a bagel with cream cheese, you have to buy them separately and then you can't get the bagel toasted, we were told flatly "No." Overall, a huge letdown as a recommended stop. The only reason it got 2 stars and not 1 is because the pastry was good and the selection was large. Everything else was a fail.< /text>< pictures>

< userid>
105922283318214063748< /userid>
< user_name>
Stephanie Han<//user_name>
<Time>1421859810934<//Time>< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>
< review>
It's an adorably quaint bakery/cafe/store with so many goodies you can feel the pounds piling on as you just take a look around. I got some of their famous chile cheese bread to eat on they way to Mammoth, and then got their ham and cheese bread, an apple pull-apart thingy, and some Pecan "kisses" (thin crispy butter cookies with pecans, YUM!!!) to enjoy on the way back. Also tried their Mule Kick sandwich for lunch on a friend's recommendation: roast beef, swiss, tomato, lettuce, sprouts, jalapenos and spicy mustard on their Mule bread--delish and had a very nice "kick" to it, so the name doesn't lie! It might have had a bit too much produce for me, though--everything was very fresh, but got a little drippy (hate that). Anyhoo, yes it does get crowded and crazy but what famous landmark doesn't? Now I know why it's so famous :)< /review>
< resp>

<gmap_id>0x80be1600fb5ec2ff:0xcfcedd18fdb08a6e< /gmap_id><Review>Gelato ice cream, and roast beef sandwich. Awesome<//Review><Name>CHRIS' PLUMBING<//Name><Response>None<//Response>< user>
100479059584578424711<//user>
</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
Quirky bakery with lots of character and so much to offer! Warm delicious bakery scents welcome you as you walk in. We went straight to the deli and ordered sandwiches, then got treats and a loaf of bread.
The sandwiches exceeded our expectations, their breads are soft with fresh crunch on the crust. We ordered the mule sandwich and the turkey club. Both very fresh tasting, great veggies and meat that falls apart. Free pickle spears (must be a home recipe, so good! Not your run of the mill Clausen's, thick juicy and flavorful!) And a cookie with each sandwich, yum!
Samples randomly around to inspire, their peach pull apart sample tasted like peach cinnamon roll, delicious!
Their isles were very narrow but the other patrons were friendly and polite, so it wasn't a bother.
In line for sweets we saw strudle, fruit cake, cookies, brittle, bread pudding, pull apparts, cinnamon rolls, gelato and so much more! I was fixing for toffee and was pleased to find some.
We loved the bread from our sandwiches, but when we went back for a loaf to buy and take with us, they were out! I asked one of the workers and she said once the racks were empty it usually means they're all out. We were about to be on our way and the worker came after us saying she could check in the deli to see if there were any left over since they had just closed the deli. How accommodating! We were overjoyed at her thoughtfulness. And happy to have a loaf to take home and enjoy. We would definitely recommend it and come back.< /Review>

(Translated by Google) This is the most famous bakery in Bishop!

The left side of the store is selling bread and sandwiches, which can be made to order and eaten in the store. In addition to bread, there are various flavors of jam and honey of different flavors.

The right side of the store sells drinks, desserts and ice cream. The gelato here is very delicious! They are made with fresh fruits, not artificial flavors or colors. They are produced in limited quantities every day. It is highly recommended ~
